      "message": "Possible SQL injection",
      "file": "app/queries/games/genre_shelf_batch.rb",
      "line": 82,
      "link": "https://brakemanscanner.org/docs/warning_types/sql_injection/",
      "code": "Game.find_by_sql(\"SELECT * FROM (\\n  SELECT games.*,\\n         ROW_NUMBER() OVER (\\n           PARTITION BY primary_genre_id\\n           ORDER BY LOWER(games.title), games.id\\n         ) AS rn\\n  FROM games\\n  WHERE primary_genre_id IN (#{genre_ids.map(&:to_i).join(\",\")})\\n) ranked\\nWHERE rn <= #{cap.to_i}\\n\".squish)",
      "render_path": null,
      "location": {
        "type": "method",
        "class": "Games::GenreShelfBatch",
        "method": "fetch_top_games"
      },
      "user_input": "genre_ids.map(&:to_i).join(\",\")",
      "confidence": "Medium",
      "cwe_id": [
        89
      ],
      "note": "Accepted: both interpolated fragments are explicitly coerced to integers before being splice into the SQL. `genre_ids.map(&:to_i).join(\",\")` produces a comma-separated list of pure integers (Ruby `to_i` returns 0 on garbage input, never a string with quotes / spaces / SQL fragments). `cap.to_i` is similarly a single integer. The query is a windowed top-N-per-genre lookup using ROW_NUMBER() — bind params can't express a dynamic IN-list of this shape cleanly, and casting to Integer is the canonical safe pattern. Brakeman can't see through `.to_i`, so the warning is a static-analysis false positive."
    },
